  "text": "Django's SQL injection prevention for raw SQL queries is implemented through a layered approach involving expression sanitization, parameter binding, and database driver parameterization.\n\n## RawSQL Expression Sanitization\n\nThe RawSQL class (django/db/models/expressions.py:1236-1268) is the primary expression type for raw SQL queries. It implements SQL injection prevention by requiring users to explicitly pass parameters separately from the SQL string:\n\n- Constructor requires both a SQL string and a params argument (line 1239)\n- The as_sql() method (line 1248) returns the SQL with parameters kept separate: it wraps the raw SQL in parentheses and returns the params as a tuple, maintaining the separation between SQL code and parameter values\n- This design forces developers to use parameterized queries where the SQL structure is fixed and values are passed separately\n\n## Raw QuerySet Method Parameter Binding\n\nThe Manager.raw() method (django/db/models/query.py:1461-1473) creates a RawQuerySet instance that handles parameter binding:\n\n- It accepts a raw_query string and params argument (line 1461)\n- Passes both the query and params to the RawQuerySet constructor (lines 1464-1469)\n- The RawQuerySet class (django/db/models/query.py:2210-2250) stores both raw_query and params as separate attributes (lines 2227, 2232)\n\n## RawQuery Execution and Parameter Adaptation\n\nThe RawQuery class (django/db/models/sql/query.py:150-220) implements the core parameter binding for raw SQL execution:\n\n- Constructor stores sql and params separately (lines 153-155)\n- The _execute_query() method (lines 203-220) implements parameter adaptation before database execution:\n  - Detects the parameter type (tuple, dict, or None) using params_type property (line 208)\n  - Uses connection.ops.adapt_unknown_value to adapt parameters to database-compatible types (line 209)\n  - For tuple params: adapts each value individually (line 211)\n  - For dict params: adapts each dictionary value (line 213)\n  - Obtains a database cursor and calls cursor.execute() with the SQL and adapted params (lines 219-220)\n\n## Cursor.execute() Parameterization Enforcement\n\nThe CursorWrapper class (django/db/backends/utils.py:17-114) enforces parameterization at the database driver level:\n\n- The execute() method (lines 78-81) delegates to _execute_with_wrappers() which applies any registered execute wrappers\n- The _execute() method (lines 94-105) is the final executor that handles the actual database call:\n  - If params is None, calls cursor.execute(sql) without parameters (line 103)\n  - If params is provided, calls cursor.execute(sql, params) (line 105)\n  - Uses wrap_database_errors context manager to catch SQL errors (line 100)\n  - Validates transaction state before execution (line 99)\n- CursorDebugWrapper (lines 117-150) extends this with query logging while maintaining the parameterization pattern\n\n## Parameter Type Adaptation\n\nThe adapt_unknown_value method (django/db/backends/base/operations.py:550-567) performs type conversion for parameters:\n\n- Handles datetime, date, time, and decimal objects by converting them to database-compatible formats\n- Returns the adapted value ready for the underlying database driver's parameterization system\n\nThis layered approach ensures that user-provided data never gets interpolated directly into SQL strings. Instead, the SQL structure is defined separately, and all user data is passed through the database driver's native parameterization mechanisms, which automatically escape and quote values appropriately for the specific database backend."
}

